components.label: Crop stage
components.tooltip:
What is the stage of the crop now:

• Sowing = planting seeds (pre-emerging stage)

• Seedling = the first visible sign of the plant emerging or appearing from the soil

• Vegetative = from the first leaf to the late whorl

• Reproductive = from the tassel to silk stage (maize), flowering (cereals, other crops)

• Maturity = cobs or ears (maize), grains and head (millet, sorghum) are visible

components.label: General health of crop
components.tooltip: Look across the field - how healthy does the crop look to you?

components.label: Farming system
components.tooltip:
How are the crops being grown:

• Seasonal = growing the same crop in a season or rainy period

• Rotation = growing different crops in each season

• Intercropping = growing two or more crops close to each other

• Push-Pull = using repellant (push) plants and trap (pull) plants

• Unknown = if not known

components.label: totalFAW
totalAAW
totalBorer
Crop damage
components.tooltip: What is the general level of damage on the crop, which may or may not be due only to FAW

components.label: Cob damaged by FAW?
components.tooltip: Do you see any damage in the cob (ear) of the maize?

components.label: Current damage in whorl and leaves?
components.tooltip: Roughly how much fresh FAW damage is on the top, young leaves and whorl? Look in the whorl (funnel) for fresh damage and frass. This is current infestation.

components.label: Previous damage on older leaves?
components.tooltip: Roughly how much previous FAW damage is on the lower, older leaves? If the damaged leaves have grown out of the whorl (funnel) and there are fresh, undamaged leaves, then the FAW caterpillar is no longer feeding in the whorl. This is old damage. You may also see scratches on the older parts of the leaves. This is damage from young larvae that may have moved into the whorl, been killed, or moved to another plant.

components.label: Natural enemies present?
components.tooltip:
Do you see any natural enemies – these are farmers’ friends:
•	Parasitoids - flies that lay their own eggs in FAW eggs and wasps that lay eggs in FAW larvae
•	Pathogens - fungus and virus that make the larvae turn white, green or brown, sometimes becoming swollen and shrivelled 
•	Predators - ants, beetles, earwigs and stinkbugs that attack the larvae

components.label: Content
components.content: A parasitoid is an organism in which one of its life stages is completed inside the pest and the pest eventually dies. Parasitoids can lay their eggs inside FAW eggs, larvae and pupa and prevent the FAW from becoming an adult.

components.label: Content
components.content: A Fall Armyworm (FAW) infected with Winthemia trinitatis eggs.

components.label: Content
components.content: A Pathogen or a germ in the oldest and broadest sense is anything that can produce disease. Typically the term is used to describe an infectious microorganism such as a virus, bacterium, protozoa, prion, or fungus.

components.label: Content
components.content: Predation is a biological interaction where one organism, the predator, kills and eats another organism, its prey. Predators may actively search for prey or sit and wait for it. When prey is detected, the predator assesses whether to attack it.

components.label: Dead larvae present?
components.tooltip: If you see any dead larvae, they may be infected by a fungus or virus. Remember that you can collect dead larvae, put them in a container, smash them and mix with water to apply on the crop.

components.label: Control undertaken
components.tooltip:
If control was done in the field, select the different methods that were used:
•	Biocontrol - the use of natural enemies
•	Biopesticide - the use of a biological pesticide (BT, neem and others)
•	Cultural - any cultural practices such as planting dates, planting with an associated crop or plant
•	Chemical pesticide - the use of a synthetic chemical pesticide (not recommended)
•	Egg-squashing - smashing the egg clusters on the top and bottom of the leaves with your thumb
•	Hand-picking - of larvae from the leaves
•	Traditional control - the use of sand, ash, soil, oils, soaps, fish soup and others
•	Plowing - deep tillage to destroy the pupae in the soil

components.label: Chemical pesticide name
components.tooltip: What is the name of the chemical pesticide that was used?

components.label: Amount of chemical pesticide (litres)
components.tooltip: How many litres were sprayed?

components.label: Biopesticide name
components.tooltip: What is the name of the biopesticide that was used?

components.label: Amount of biopesticide (litres)
components.tooltip: How many litres were sprayed?

components.label: Local control type(s)
components.tooltip: What type(s) of traditional or local methods of control did you use?

components.label: Please fill out the following information
Trap ID
components.tooltip: Write the unique ID for the trap. Remember that each trap should have its own ID, for example KE000001 where KE is the country code of Kenya and 000001 is trap no. 1. The ID should be clearly written on the trap.

components.label: Trap location
components.tooltip: Where is the trap located? Remember that traps should be placed either in the centre or on the edge of a field.

components.label: FAW confirmed
components.tooltip: Adult moth catches that you are certain are FAW. If in doubt, remember to compare with a photo of FAW.

components.label: FAW suspected
components.tooltip: Adult moth catches that you think may be FAW but you are not certain

components.label: Other species
components.tooltip: Moth catches that are not FAW

components.label: Trap type
components.tooltip: What type of trap are you checking? Bucket and sticky delta traps are the two main types of traps used for FAW. Bucket traps are preferred because they are more durable and rugged, can be used for more than one season, and are easier to manage.

components.label: Trap condition
components.tooltip: Is the current trap in good working condition or is it broken?

components.label: Lure name
components.tooltip: What is the name or brand of the lure? Remember that only FAW lures should be used to monitor FAW.

components.label: Trap replaced?
components.tooltip: Has the trap been replaced? Remember that broken traps should be replaced.

validate.customMessage: Please select a date prior to the date of submission

components.label: Lure replaced?
components.tooltip: Has the lure been replaced? Remember to replace lures and kill strips every 3–6 weeks.

components.label: Date lured replaced
components.tooltip: Indicate the general date when the lure was last replaced

components.label: Irrigation
components.tooltip: Is the crop irrigated or rain-fed; if you do not know, select Unknown

components.label: Crop stage
components.tooltip:
What is the stage of the crop now:

• Sowing = planting seeds (pre-emerging stage)

• Seedling = the first visible sign of the plant emerging or appearing from the soil

• Vegetative = from the first leaf to the late whorl

• Reproductive = from the tassel to silk stage (maize), flowering (cereals, other crops)

• Maturity = cobs or ears (maize), grains and head (millet, sorghum) are visible

components.label: General health of crop
components.tooltip: Look across the field - how healthy does the crop look to you?

components.label: Farming system
components.tooltip:
How are the crops being grown:

• Seasonal = growing the same crop in a season or rainy period

• Rotation = growing different crops in each season

• Intercropping = growing two or more crops close to each other

• Push-Pull = using repellant (push) plants and trap (pull) plants

• Unknown = if not known
